<BaseLayout title="About — Arian Lopez" description="Software engineer writing about distributed systems, Redis, and AI-native developer tools.">
  <section class="about">
    <h1>About</h1>

    <p>
      I'm a software engineer from Havana, Cuba, based in South Florida. I've spent most of my career
      working on backend infrastructure — the kind of systems where getting the caching strategy wrong
      means your Redis cluster hits 100% memory at 3am, and where "just add another instance" is never
      actually the answer.
    </p>

    <p>
      Right now I'm at UKG, working on platform engineering — API infrastructure, tenant lifecycle
      systems, and internal tooling. Before that I was at Salesforce for about four and a half years,
      building the inventory platform behind Commerce Cloud. And before that, PwC, where I got my
      first real exposure to AI through building modules for an IBM Watson-powered assistant.
    </p>

    <h2>What I think about</h2>

    <p>
      I'm fascinated by the space between platform engineering and AI. Not the "sprinkle some LLM
      on it" kind — the kind where you give AI tools actual structural knowledge about your codebase
      and they go from generating plausible-looking code to generating code that actually fits.
    </p>

    <p>
      That's what led me to build <a href="/projects">Trabuco</a>. It started as a project generator
      because I was tired of spending the first sprint of every new service on Maven boilerplate. Then
      I noticed AI coding assistants worked dramatically better on the projects it generated — the clean
      module boundaries gave them context they couldn't get from a messy monolith. So I kept going:
      AI migration pipelines, MCP integration, context files for five different coding assistants.
      It became less about scaffolding and more about what an AI-native project structure actually looks like.
    </p>

    <h2>Writing</h2>

    <p>
      I write about things I've worked through — Redis performance debugging, rate limiting strategies
      for multi-tenant systems, caching architectures. Production problems, not theoretical ones.
      If I'm writing about it, it's because my team hit it and we had to figure it out.
    </p>

    <h2>Background</h2>

    <p>
      I studied Computer Science at the Polytechnic Institute of Havana (CUJAE) and later got my B.S.
      at Florida International University. I'm based in Pembroke Pines, FL.
    </p>

